00:00:00.167 --> 00:00:02.384
- [Voiceover] So let's say
we have the radical equation

00:00:02.384 --> 00:00:06.006
two-x minus one is equal

00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:10.429
to the square root of eight minus x.

00:00:10.429 --> 00:00:13.041
So we already have the
radical isolated on one side

00:00:13.041 --> 00:00:13.842
of the equation.

00:00:13.842 --> 00:00:15.696
So, we might say, "Well, let's
just get rid of the radical.

00:00:15.696 --> 00:00:18.126
"Let's square both
sides of this equation."

00:00:18.126 --> 00:00:19.728
So we might say that
this is the same thing

00:00:19.728 --> 00:00:22.967
as two-x minus one squared

00:00:22.967 --> 00:00:27.776
is equal to the square
root of eight minus x,

00:00:27.776 --> 00:00:30.447
eight minus x squared,
and then we would get,

00:00:30.447 --> 00:00:31.999
let's see, two-x minus one squared

00:00:31.999 --> 00:00:35.006
is four x-squared minus four-x

00:00:35.006 --> 00:00:38.922
plus one is equal to eight minus x.

00:00:38.922 --> 00:00:42.788
Now we have to be very,
very, very careful here.

00:00:42.788 --> 00:00:45.187
We might feel, "Okay we
did legitimate operations.

00:00:45.187 --> 00:00:47.044
"We did the same thing to both sides.

00:00:47.044 --> 00:00:50.721
"That these are equivalent equations."

00:00:50.721 --> 00:00:52.907
But, they aren't quite equivalent.

00:00:52.907 --> 00:00:54.346
Because when you're squaring something,

00:00:54.346 --> 00:00:55.228
one way to think about it,

00:00:55.228 --> 00:00:58.084
is when you're squaring it,
you're losing information.

00:00:58.084 --> 00:01:00.615
So, for example, this would be true

00:01:00.615 --> 00:01:04.566
even if the original
equation were two-x...

00:01:04.566 --> 00:01:06.199
Let me, this in a different color.

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:09.159
